comment.editorialComment: MPV is one of the more stable sectors these days which is partly driven by the reduction in volumes over the past few years and also by the fact that most vehicles in this sector represent good value for money from both a trade and retail point of view. Seasonality does come into play a bit but generally, people buy cars from this sector based on reasons of practicality rather than desire, so the time of the year becomes less important. However, normal market forces are likely to have an effect and after what will have been a couple of fairly stable months we would expect to see values adjusted by around -2.0% as we approach the end of the year.

It is normal for the market to toughen a little as we enter into December and this sector will not be immune from that factor. Volumes will probably be quite high as we go into the month and many of the big vendors will need to offload stock before the end of the year. This normally results in pressure on wholesale values as the appetite to sell doesn’t always match the appetite to buy. Having said that, there are still people out buying in December but they will only buy if the money is right which tend to put pressure on values as we get towards the middle of the month. This means that we would expect to see used values drop by around -2.0% during the course of the month.

Over the past few years, volumes have reduced slightly in this sector as more people switch into vehicles from the ever growing SUV sector. However, that doesn’t mean that there isn’t a strong demand for available product and given the fact that the market usually strengthens in January then we should expect to see some sort of increase in values as we go through the month. We can expect to see some fresh stock coming into the market from some of the bigger wholesale suppliers but that is unlikely to have any detrimental effect. Our expectation is that values will rise by around 1.0% during the course of the month.
